2. RESTful Services (API Architecture) ğŸŒ
ğŸ§  Logic:REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for designing distributed systems, primarily web services ($\mathbf{APIs}$). A service adhering to this style is called RESTful.Goal: Create simple, scalable, and stateless communication using standard $\mathbf{HTTP~methods}$ to interact with resources (which are identified by $\mathbf{URLs}$).Key REST principles:Stateless: The server does not store client session information between requests.Resource-Based: Everything is treated as a resource (e.g., /users, /products/1).Use HTTP Methods: Use standard HTTP verbs to perform CRUD operations.ğŸ“Œ Example (Mapping HTTP Methods to CRUD):HTTP MethodCRUD OperationDescriptionGETReadRetrieve a resource or a collection of resources.POSTCreateSubmit data to create a new resource.PUT/PATCHUpdateUpdate an existing resource.DELETEDeleteRemove a resource.ğŸ¤¹â€â™€ï¸ Java Code (Spring Boot REST Controller):Javaimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

// Marks the class as a REST controller
@RestController 
// Base URL path
@RequestMapping("/api/users") 
public class UserController {
    
    // Handles GET /api/users
    @GetMapping 
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        // ... return list of users
        return userService.findAll();
    }
    
    // Handles POST /api/users
    @PostMapping 
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User newUser) {
        // @RequestBody maps incoming JSON/XML to the User object
        return userService.save(newUser);
    }
}
